</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="697" pageId="14" pageNumber="695" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[811,1456,1523,2028]" box="[813,957,1523,1549]" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[811,1456,1523,2028]" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">
Despite a swampy paleoenvironment that might be suitable for their occurrence and preservation, anurans are relatively scarce among the microvertebrate material from Angeac-Charente. In Angeac-Charente, anurans are represented by isolated, fragmentary bones, such as fused zeugopods (
<figureCitation box="[1318,1447,1682,1709]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="16.[132,143,778,795]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,733]" captionTargetId="figure-570@16.[132,1455,215,734]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 10. — Anuran remains from Angeac-Charente:A, B, right tibiofibular of Anura indet.(ANG M-63) in anterior (A) and posterior (B) views; C, D, urostyle of Anura indet. (ANG M- 64) in dorsal (C) and ventral (D) views. Scale bar represents: A, B, 5 mm; C, D, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902055/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">Fig. 10A, B</figureCitation>
) and urostyles (
<figureCitation box="[970,1101,1714,1741]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="16.[132,143,778,795]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,733]" captionTargetId="figure-570@16.[132,1455,215,734]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 10. — Anuran remains from Angeac-Charente:A, B, right tibiofibular of Anura indet.(ANG M-63) in anterior (A) and posterior (B) views; C, D, urostyle of Anura indet. (ANG M- 64) in dorsal (C) and ventral (D) views. Scale bar represents: A, B, 5 mm; C, D, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902055/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">Fig. 10C, D</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[811,1456,1523,2028]" lastBlockId="16.[130,775,885,1135]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="697" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">
Among fused zeugopods, some are sufficiently well preserved to allow their identification.For instance, the general shape and length (even if the proximal part is missing) of specimen ANG M-63 (
<figureCitation box="[890,1014,1841,1868]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="16.[132,143,778,795]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,733]" captionTargetId="figure-570@16.[132,1455,215,734]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 10. — Anuran remains from Angeac-Charente:A, B, right tibiofibular of Anura indet.(ANG M-63) in anterior (A) and posterior (B) views; C, D, urostyle of Anura indet. (ANG M- 64) in dorsal (C) and ventral (D) views. Scale bar represents: A, B, 5 mm; C, D, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902055/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">Fig. 10A, B</figureCitation>
), as well as several other features, allow its identification as a tibiofibula (
<bibRefCitation author="THOMAS S. C." box="[1141,1291,1873,1899]" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Zooarchaeology" pageId="14" pageNumber="695" pagination="2 - 8" part="10" refId="ref50147" refString="THOMAS S. C. 1996. - Differentiation of selected frog (Rana) and toad (Bufo) using morphological and osteometric traits. Canadian Zooarchaeology 10: 2 - 8." title="Differentiation of selected frog (Rana) and toad (Bufo) using morphological and osteometric traits" type="journal article" year="1996">Thomas 1996</bibRefCitation>
): presence of a tibiofibular groove, deeper on the anterior face, between the fused zeugopod, and presence of a tibial crest on the anterior face (
<figureCitation box="[868,964,1969,1995]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="16.[132,143,778,795]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,733]" captionTargetId="figure-570@16.[132,1455,215,734]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 10. — Anuran remains from Angeac-Charente:A, B, right tibiofibular of Anura indet.(ANG M-63) in anterior (A) and posterior (B) views; C, D, urostyle of Anura indet. (ANG M- 64) in dorsal (C) and ventral (D) views. Scale bar represents: A, B, 5 mm; C, D, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902055/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="695">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
). Among well-known Early Cretaceous anuran families are the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1843" box="[974,1063,2001,2027]" class="Amphibia" family="Alytidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="14" pageNumber="695" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Alytidae</taxonomicName>
(= “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Günther" authorityYear="1858" box="[1106,1271,2001,2028]" family="Discoglossidae" pageId="14" pageNumber="695" rank="family">Discoglossidae</taxonomicName>
”), but within this family, the tibia and fibula remain unfused (
<bibRefCitation author="ROCEK Z." bookContentInfo="1496 p." box="[626,758,885,911]" editor="HEATWOLE H. &amp; CAR- ROLL R. L." journalOrPublisher="Surrey Beatty &amp; Sons, Chipping Norton" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" refId="ref47987" refString="ROCEK Z. 2000. - Mesozoic anurans, in HEATWOLE H. &amp; CAR- ROLL R. L. (eds), Amphibian Biology. Volume 4. Palaeontology - The Evolutionary History of Amphibians. Surrey Beatty &amp; Sons, Chipping Norton, 1496 p." title="Mesozoic anurans" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Amphibian Biology. Volume 4. Palaeontology - The Evolutionary History of Amphibians" year="2000">Roček 2000</bibRefCitation>
), unlike the Angeac-Charente specimen.
</paragraph>
