<paragraph blockId="16.[130,775,885,1135]" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">
The specimen ANG M-64 (
<figureCitation box="[456,587,949,975]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="16.[132,143,778,795]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,733]" captionTargetId="figure-570@16.[132,1455,215,734]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 10. — Anuran remains from Angeac-Charente:A, B, right tibiofibular of Anura indet.(ANG M-63) in anterior (A) and posterior (B) views; C, D, urostyle of Anura indet. (ANG M- 64) in dorsal (C) and ventral (D) views. Scale bar represents: A, B, 5 mm; C, D, 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902055/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Fig. 10C, D</figureCitation>
) bears two broad and flattened articular facets anteriorly, and a small crest arises from its dorsal face. Four weakly marked ridges can be seen alongside this small crest, two on each side (
<figureCitation box="[576,655,1044,1070]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[132,143,1917,1934]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-15@15.[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIG. 9. — Albanerpetontid remains from Angeac-Charente: A, B, left dentary of Albanerpetontidae indet. (ANG M-101) in lingual (A) and dorsal (B) views; C, premaxillary of Albanerpetontidae indet. (ANG M-102) in ventrolingual view; D, E, left maxillary of Albanerpetontidae indet. (ANG M-51) in labial (D) and lingual (E) views; F, G, dentary fragment of Albanerpetontidae indet. (ANG M-35) in labial view showing foramina discussed in the text (F) and lingual (G) view; H, distal end of a left humerus of Albanerpetontidae indet. (ANG M-36) in ventral view; I-K, dorsal vertebra of Albanerpetontidae indet. (ANG M-103) in dorsal (I), anterior (J) and lateral (K) views. Scale bars: A-E, H-K, 400 µm; F, G, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902053" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902053/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
). This morphology identifies it as a urostyle. To date, incompleteness of the material limits comparisons with other Mesozoic anurans.
</paragraph>
